The '''second series of the British crime drama ''[[Broadchurch]]''''' began airing on the [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] broadcast network in the United Kingdom on 5 January 2015. The eight-episode series focused on the continuing fallout of the murder of 11-year-old Danny Latimer in the fictional, close-knit coastal town of Broadchurch in [[Dorset]], [[United Kingdom]]. The series focused on the effect of Joe Miller's trial on his wife, [[Police ranks of the United Kingdom#Detectives|DS]] Ellie Miller; the Latimer family's struggle to achieve a normal life; and the impact new revelations have on the town.

Although ''Broadchurch'' was conceived as a trilogy, the second series was only announced on 22 April 2013 as series one ended. Writing occurred over most of the following year, with series creator and lead writer [[Chris Chibnall]] using a plot-development process he used for the first series. The return of series stars [[Olivia Colman]] and [[David Tennant]] and some of their returning co-stars was reported by the media in the fall of 2013, although both returning and new cast members were not formally announced by ITV until May 2014.

Filming on ''Broadchurch'' series two began in late May 2014, under the supervision of four directors. Extensive efforts were undertaken to keep the plot secret from the cast, crew, and public. Extensive location shooting occurred along the United Kingdom's [[Jurassic Coast]] and in [[South West England]]. [[Iceland]]ic musician and composer [[<U+00D3>lafur Arnalds]] returned as the series' musical and sound composer.

==Production approval==
[[File:EveMyles.JPG|thumb|Eve Myles joined the cast of series two.]]
While conceiving and writing the first series in 2012, ''Broadchurch'' creator and lead writer Chris Chibnall designed his story to be told as a trilogy.<ref name=trilogy>{{cite news|url=http://www.broadcastnow.co.uk/news/commissioning/featherstone-broadchurch-planned-as-trilogy/5062879.article|last=White|first=Peter|title=Featherstone: Broadchurch 'planned as trilogy'|newspaper=Broadcast Now|date=24 October 2013|accessdate=10 November 2014}}</ref><ref name=cultbox>{{cite web|url=http://www.cultbox.co.uk/news/headlines/6511-broadchurch-creator-unsure-about-series-2 |title='Broadchurch' creator unsure about Series 2|publisher=CultBox|date=29 March 2013|accessdate=23 April 2013}}</ref> Series one was written to work both as the first part of this trilogy as well as a self-contained drama. The first series had to be self-contained, he felt, in case the show did not do well in the ratings and a second series was not commissioned.<ref name=cultbox /><ref name="rtstalk">{{cite news|url=http://www.rts.org.uk/broadchurch-anatomy-hit-%E2%80%93-event-report|last=Bell|first=Matthew|title=Broadchurch: Anatomy of a hit|publisher=Television|date=January 2014|accessdate=24 November 2014}}</ref> When Chibnall pitched series one to ITV in the fall of 2012, he also pitched series two and three at the same time.<ref name=tworeturnsnottingham>{{cite news|url=http://www.nottinghampost.com/Broadchurch-series-ITV-drama-returns/story-25791735-detail/story.html|title=Broadchurch series two: ITV drama returns|newspaper=Nottingham Post|date=4 January 2015|accessdate=4 January 2015}}</ref>

As series one aired, Chibnall had discussions with ITV executives about commissioning series two. According to Chibnall, ITV was more concerned that people were enjoying the show than they were with the series' ratings (which were very high). ITV agreed to [[green-light]] series two about midway through the airing of series one.  This allowed Chibnall to announce series two as a "gift" to viewers at the end of series one, so the public would not remain in suspense about a second series.<ref name=chibnallsecret>{{cite news|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/british-tv/s218/broadchurch/interviews/a482834/broadchurch-chris-chibnall-qa-i-asked-to-keep-series-two-secret.html#~oXHlOSv3SpnXhg|last=Jeffrey|first=Morgan|title='Broadchurch' Chris Chibnall Q&A: 'I asked to keep series two secret'|newspaper=Digital Spy|date=20 May 2013|accessdate=6 December 2014}}</ref>

The final episode of series one finished on 22 April 2013 with a caption reading "''Broadchurch'' Will Return". ITV executives confirmed that same night that a second series of ''Broadchurch'' had been commissioned, with production to begin in 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/british-tv/s218/broadchurch/news/a475339/broadchurch-will-return-for-second-series-big-reveal-in-itv-drama.html#~oVgMrDF5bNR0pl|last=Fletcher|first=Alex|title='Broadchurch' will return for second series: Big reveal in ITV drama|website=Digital Spy|date=22 April 2013|accessdate=10 November 2014}}</ref> Following this episode, an extra scene was released on [[YouTube]] depicting Danny Latimer's wake. This video also ended with the words "''Broadchurch'' Will Return".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbcamerica.com/anglophenia/2013/09/longing-for-more-broadchurch-here-are-extra-scenes/|last=Rozen|first=Leah|title=Longing for More 'Broadchurch'? Here Are Extra Scenes|website=BBC America|date=30 September 2013|accessdate=10 November 2014}}</ref> Olivia Colman said that Chibnall telephoned the cast of series one before the announcement to tell them that series two had been greenlit, and outlined his concepts for series two.<ref name=halinawatts>{{cite news|url=http://www.mirror.co.uk/news/uk-news/broadchurch-star-olivia-colman-fears-1857368|last=Watts|first=Halina|title=Broadchurch star Olivia Colman fears her career could be killed off as she gets older|newspaper=The Daily Mirror|date=28 April 2013|accessdate=9 December 2014}}</ref>

Jane Featherstone and Chris Chibnall continued as [[executive producer]]s of the program in series two,<ref name=dorsetechofirst /> with [[Richard Stokes (producer)|Richard Stokes]] returning as [[Television producer|producer]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.walesonline.co.uk/whats-on/whats-on-news/picture-broadchurch-series-two-cast-7156426|last=Jones|first=Hannah|title=First look: New Broadchurch cast line up for series read through|newspaper=Wales Online|date=22 May 2014|accessdate=3 December 2014}}</ref> Chibnall also acted as lead writer.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2014-01-30/broadchurch-writer-on-david-tennants-fears-of-being-killed-off-hes-right-to-be-worried|last=Lazarus|first=Susanna|title=Broadchurch writer on David Tennant's fears of being killed off: "He's right to be worried"|newspaper=Radio Times|date=30 January 2014|accessdate=25 July 2014}}</ref> ITV executive creative director Tony Pipes declined to reveal the budget for series two, but said it was about the same as other major drama series at the network.<ref name=campellikickoff>{{cite news|url=http://www.broadcastnow.co.uk/broadcasters/broadchurch-marketing-kicks-off-with-flock-to-unlock-trailer/5080974.article?blocktitle=Latest-news&contentID=870|last=Campelli|first=Matthew|title=Broadchurch marketing kicks off with 'flock to unlock' trailer|newspaper=Broadcast|date=11 December 2014|accessdate=11 December 2014}}</ref>
{{clear}}

==Writing==
Chibnall told the ''[[Daily Mirror]]'' in the summer of 2013 that "the focus of the next series will be on how the shattered community rebuilds itself after the grisly events" of series one.<ref name=jefferiesexhumed>{{cite news|url=http://www.mirror.co.uk/tv/tv-news/broadchurch-series-2-pictures-spoilers-3627032|last=Jefferies|first=Mark|title= Broadchurch series 2 pictures spoilers: David Tennant and Olivia Colman on set but whose grave is being exhumed?|newspaper=The Daily Mirror|date=30 May 2014|accessdate=25 July 2014}}</ref> Series one actor [[Will Mellor]] strongly implied in an interview that a new murder would not be the focus of the new season,<ref name=jefferiesexhumed /> while actor [[David Tennant]] told the ''[[Associated Press]]'' that the series would go in a "very unexpected direction" which he called "as gripping as the first season".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://metronews.ca/scene/1198915/tennant-new-direction-for-broadchurch-season-2/|last=Neff|first=Lauri|title=Tennant: New Direction for 'Broadchurch' Season 2|newspaper=Associated Press|date=30 October 2014|accessdate=30 October 2014}}</ref> While grief was the key theme of series one, Chibnall chose an entirely different theme for series two.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2014-12-29/broadchurch-writer-chris-chibnall-on-series-two-grief-is-not-our-driving-emotion-this-year|last=Delgado|first=Kasia|title=Broadchurch writer Chris Chibnall on series two: 'Grief is not our driving emotion this year'|newspaper=Radio Times|date=29 December 2014|accessdate=4 January 2015}}</ref> Tennant described series two as "Tonally, it's the same show, but structurally, it's completely different."<ref name=tweets>{{cite news|url=http://www.westerndailypress.co.uk/Broadchurch-ITV-drama-returns-Monday-night-tell/story-25802994-detail/story.html|title=Broadchurch: The ITV drama returns on Monday night to tell different story|newspaper=Western Daily Press|date=4 January 2015|accessdate=4 January 2015}}</ref>

Chibnall said he mapped out the show's plot and characters on several [[whiteboard]]s in his office before beginning the writing process. "You have to be very methodical," he said about plotting ''Broadchurch''. "It's like a mathematical puzzle where you put all these blocks together and move them around for the most satisfying thing."<ref name=clue /> Chibnall was assisted in [[storyboard]]ing series two by his good friend Sam Hoyle, a television script executive who also worked with him in laying out series one. "By the time I sat down to type scenes and dialogue," Chibnall said, "I'd already done quite a lot of work."<ref name=earledream>{{cite news|url=http://www.standard.co.uk/showbiz/celebrity-news/broadchurch-creator-chris-chibnall-talks-david-tennant-and-why-olivia-colman-is-a-writers-dream-9958324.html|last=Earle|first=Toby|title=Broadchurch creator Chris Chibnall talks David Tennant and why Olivia Colman is a 'writer's dream'|newspaper=London Evening Standard|date=5 January 2015|accessdate=5 January 2015}}</ref> As early as mid-July 2013, Chibnall told the ''Daily Mirror'' that he had finalized the plot and written the second series' first and last scenes, and was now working on the rest of the script.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mirror.co.uk/tv/tv-news/broadchurch-writer-chris-chibnall-written-2045178|last=Methven|first=Nicola|title=Broadchurch writer has written first and last scenes of second series and now 'just needs to fill other eight hours'|newspaper=The Daily Mirror|date=11 July 2013|accessdate=3 December 2014}}</ref> Chibnall also said that the second series' themes, story, and basic mysteries are clearly established by the end of the first episode.<ref name=Campellithrill>{{cite news|url=http://www.broadcastnow.co.uk/broadcasters/chris-chibnall-broadchurch-return-to-be-more-thrilling/5081259.article|last=Campelli|first=Matthew|title=Chris Chibnall: Broadchurch return to be more thrilling|newspaper=Broadcast|date=18 December 2014|accessdate=18 December 2014}}</ref> Much of series two draws on plot elements established in series one. Lead actor Olivia Colman noted "You find out very early in the first episode which direction it's going in and it's an instant, 'Whoooa!'. Chris set up a lot of things we never even thought about in the first series and now they've come to the fore. At the read-through we were going, 'You sneaky b*****d'."<ref name=strangback>{{cite news|url=http://www.mirror.co.uk/tv/tv-news/broadchurch-back-your-guide-series-4893264|last=Strang|first=Fay|title=Broadchurch is back! Your guide to series two - everything you need to know|newspaper=The Daily Mirror|date=30 December 2014|accessdate=4 January 2015}}</ref> Chibnall ended series two with what he described as "the cheekiest cliffhanger yet <U+2014> a real shocker".<ref name=cheekiest>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2882161/Dark-secrets-Broadchurch-2-Writer-month-s-hotly-anticipated-sequel-warns-viewers-brace-upset-shock-cheekiest-cliffhanger-yet.html|last=Hastings|first=Chris|title=EXCLUSIVE: Dark secrets of Broadchurch 2: Writer of next month's hotly anticipated sequel warns viewers to 'brace yourselves for upset and shock with the cheekiest cliffhanger yet'|newspaper=The Sunday Mail|date=20 December 2014|accessdate=20 December 2014}}</ref>

In August 2014, [[Erin Kelly (author)|Erin Kelly]], author of the ''Broadchurch'' novelisation, said that Chibnall inserted a one-line clue about series two into her book three days before printing was due to begin. Kelly said the clue is revealed in the early pages. Although it does not spoil the plot, she said, it does provide a hint about it.<ref name=clue>{{cite news|url=http://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/news/broadchurch-series-2-plot-clue-hidden-in-new-spinoff-book-9662261.html|last=Greenwood|first=Carl|title=Broadchurch Season 2 Spoilers: Creator Chris Chibnall Hides Plot Clues in Novel Adaptation of Show|newspaper=The Daily Mirror|date=12 August 2014|accessdate=27 August 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mirror.co.uk/tv/tv-news/broadchurch-season-2-spoilers-creator-4041518|last=Sherwin|first=Adam|title=Broadchurch Series 2: Plot Clue Hidden in New Spin-Off Book|newspaper=The Independent|date=11 August 2014|accessdate=27 August 2014}}</ref> The clue involved the argument the postman had with Danny Latimer. Jack Marshall identifies the location as near Jocelyn Knight's home. On 19 December 2014, ITV revealed that Charlotte Rampling's character is named Jocelyn Knight.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2014-12-19/who-is-charlotte-ramplings-broadchurch-character-jocelyn-knight-a-hidden-clue-could-reveal-all|last=Lazarus|first=Susanna|title=Who is Charlotte Rampling's Broadchurch character Jocelyn Knight? A hidden clue could reveal all...|newspaper=Radio Times|date=19 December 2014}}</ref>

==Casting==
[[File:Charlotte Rampling Cannes 2011.jpg|thumb|The role of a [[barrister]] in the [[Crown Prosecution Service]] was written specifically for Charlotte Rampling.]]
According to Olivia Colman, Chris Chibnall telephoned the series one cast in April 2013 and secured their verbal assent to return for another season.<ref name=halinawatts /> But it wasn't clear who would be returning. Jodie Whittaker said the cast was told during the week between episodes seven and eight of series one that ''Broadchurch'' was being brought back for a second season. But Chibnall did not tell the actors who would be returning for series two.<ref name=grahamkeeping>{{cite news|url=http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2015-01-05/broadchurch-david-tennant-and-olivia-colman-on-keeping-the-secrets-of-series-two|last=Graham|first=Alison|title=Broadchurch: David Tennant and Olivia Colman on keeping the secrets of series two|newspaper=Radio Times|date=5 January 2015|accessdate=5 January 2015}}</ref>

David Tennant and Olivia Colman both agreed to star in series two.<ref name=readingspotted>{{cite news|url=http://www.getreading.co.uk/news/local-news/you-spotted-stars-broadchurch-reading-7501110|last=Hamilton|first=Sarah|title=Have you spotted the stars of Broadchurch in Reading town centre?|newspaper=Reading Post|date=24 July 2014|accessdate=24 July 2014}}</ref> Neither actor was obligated to return, but without them, Chibnall said, "We would not have done it, absolutely. Luckily they wanted to come back because they weren't contracted to."<ref name=echofilmingends /> Chibnall initially expressed his opinion that Tennant would be unable to return, due to both Tennant's heavy work schedule as well as character Alec Hardy's health problems.<ref name=accent>{{cite news|url=http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2014-01-30/broadchurch-creator-chris-chibnall-david-tennants-us-accent-is-fantastic|last=Lazarus|first=Susanna|title=Broadchurch creator Chris Chibnall: David Tennant's US accent is 'fantastic'|newspaper=Radio Times|date=30 January 2014|accessdate=6 December 2014}}</ref> ''[[Attitude (magazine)|Attitude]]'' magazine went so far as to call Tennant's return "unlikely".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://attitude.co.uk/david-tennant-unlikely-return-broadchurch-series-two/|last=Rigby|first=Sam|title=David Tennant unlikely to return for 'Broadchurch' series two|newspaper=Attitude|date=31 January 2014|accessdate=6 December 2014}}</ref> Nevertheless, Colman and Tennant's participation was first reported by the ''Daily Mirror'' in late October 2013.<ref name=mysterydeepens>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/tvshowbiz/article-2477709/MAIL-ON-SUNDAY-DIARY-Catherine-Zeta-Jones-play-promiscuous-wife-new-film-split-Michael-Douglas.html|title=Mystery deepens in Broadchurch sequel|newspaper=The Daily Mail|date=26 October 2013|accessdate=3 November 2014}}</ref> Colman confirmed her participation on 5 November 2013.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2013-11-05/olivia-colman-confirms-her-broadchurch-series-2-return|last=Dowell|first=Ben|title=Olivia Colman confirms her Broadchurch series 2 return|newspaper=Radio Times|date=5 November 2013|accessdate=3 December 2014}}</ref> Tennant denied being cast on the show in February 2014, saying "I'm still waiting" to hear if his character would be in the second series,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mirror.co.uk/tv/tv-news/broadchurch-remake-david-tennant-describes-3172307|last=Nattrass|first=J.J.|title=David Tennant describes working on Broadchurch remake Gracepoint as 'a very peculiar experience'|newspaper=The Daily Mirror|date=22 February 2014|accessdate=3 December 2014}}</ref> but his participation was attested to in March 2014 by co-star [[Jodie Whittaker]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dorsetecho.co.uk/news/11084308.David_Tennant_hinted_to_make_Broadchurch_return_for_second_series/|title=David Tennant hinted to return to Broadchurch cast|newspaper=Dorset Echo|date=18 March 2014|accessdate=3 December 2014}}</ref> Colman and Tennant's casting was officially announced by ITV on 12 May 2014 by the ''[[Radio Times]]''.<ref name=lazaruscasting />

Other returning cast members included [[Andrew Buchan]] ("Mark Latimer"), [[Arthur Darvill]] ("Rev. Paul Coates"), Jodie Whittaker ("Beth Latimer"), Charlotte Beaumont ("Chloe Latimer"), [[Joe Sims (actor)|Joe Sims]] ("Nigel Carter"),<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mirror.co.uk/tv/tv-news/broadchurch-series-2-first-picture-3586898#ixzz38PzG8HeR|last=Greenwood|first=Carl|title=Broadchurch series 2 first picture: Olivia Colman and David Tennant joined by new cast members|newspaper=The Daily Mirror|date=22 May 2014|accessdate=24 July 2014}}</ref> [[Carolyn Pickles]] ("Maggie Radcliffe"), [[Jonathan Bailey (actor)|Jonathan Bailey]] ("Olly Stevens"),<ref name=filmingends>{{cite news|url=http://www.bournemouthecho.co.uk/news/11540687.Eight_reasons_we_can___t_wait_to_see_Broadchurch_2/|title=Eight Reasons We Can't Wait to See Broadchurch 2|newspaper=Bournemouth Echo|date=20 October 2014|accessdate=24 October 2014}}</ref> [[Pauline Quirke]] ("Susan Wright"),<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/femail/article-2529899/Linda-Robson-Pauline-Quirke-Lesley-Joseph-reveal-time-ripe-Birds-Feather-revival.html|last=Fryer|first=Jane|title=The Birds are back! 15 years on, Linda Robson, Pauline Quirke and Lesley Joseph reveal why the time is ripe for a revival|newspaper=The Daily Mail|date=27 December 2013|accessdate=9 November 2014}}</ref><ref name=colmaninwey>{{cite news|url=http://www.dorsetecho.co.uk/news/11327567.Olivia_Colman_in_Weymouth_for_Broadchurch_2_filming/|title=Olivia Colman in Weymouth for Broadchurch 2 filming|newspaper=Dorset Echo|date=8 July 2014|accessdate= 6 August 2014}}</ref> [[Tanya Franks]] ("Lucy Stevens"), [[Simone McAullay]] ("Becca Fisher"), and Adam Wilson ("Tom Miller") are returning cast members.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/british-tv/s218/broadchurch/news/a615969/broadchurch-series-2-trailer-debuts-as-january-5-premiere-date-confirmed.html|last=Rigby|first=Sam|title=Updated: Broadchurch series 2 trailer debuts as January 5 premiere date confirmed|newspaper=Digital Spy|date=11 December 2014|accessdate=11 December 2014}}</ref> Darvill confirmed his casting for series two on 17 September 2013.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mirror.co.uk/tv/tv-news/broadchurch-arthur-darvill-confirms-role-2281876|last=Walker|first=Danny|title=Arthur Darvill to return to Broadchurch series two, but actor is unsure if it will be 'an episode or a whole series'|newspaper=The Daily Mirror|date=18 September 2013|accessdate=3 December 2014}}</ref> Buchan and Whittaker's participation was announced on 12 May 2014.<ref name=lazaruscasting /> Beaumont's return was reported on 30 May 2014 when ''[[Metro (British newspaper)|Metro]]'' printed photographs of her filming a scene with other cast members.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://metro.co.uk/2014/05/30/broadchurch-fans-get-excited-filming-on-series-two-is-underway-and-here-are-the-photos-to-prove-it-4744713/|last=Westbrook|first=Caroline|title='Broadchurch' fans get excited: Filming on series two is underway, and here are the photos to prove it|newspaper=Metro|date=30 May 2014|accessdate=3 December 2014}}</ref> Sims' casting was finally revealed in late August 2014, when the media reported he was shooting scenes for series two.<ref name=simsreturns /> Actor [[Will Mellor]]{{'s}} character (alleged psychic Steve Connolly)<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mirror.co.uk/tv/tv-news/mellor-club-helped-beat-depression-4176597|last=White|first=Vikki|title=Will Mellor: 'In The Club' helped me beat depression after unemployment and sister's death|newspaper=The Daily Mirror|date=6 September 2014|accessdate=9 November 2014}}</ref> and actress [[Vicky McClure]]{{'s}} character (journalist Karen White) do not return in series two.<ref name=lazaruscertain>{{cite news|url=http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2015-01-02/broadchurch-series-two-absolutely-everything-we-know-for-certain|last=Lazarus|first=Susanna|title=Broadchurch series two: absolutely everything we know for certain|newspaper=Radio Times|date=2 January 2015|accessdate=4 January 2015}}</ref> Actor [[Matthew Gravelle]]{{'s}} return was never confirmed prior to airing.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ibtimes.co.uk/broadchurch-series-2-how-will-itvs-hit-crime-drama-live-hype-1481934|last=Skipper|first=Ben|title=Broadchurch series 2: How will ITV's hit crime drama live up to the hype?|newspaper=International Business Times|date=5 January 2015|accessdate=5 January 2015}}</ref>

Casting for ''Broadchurch'' series one was overseen by [[Casting (performing arts)#Casting director|casting directors]] Kelly Valentine Hendry and Victor Jenkins of VHJ Casting.<ref name=itvpressrelease /> New series two cast members included [[James D'Arcy]], [[Marianne Jean-Baptiste]], [[Eve Myles]], [[Charlotte Rampling]], [[Meera Syal]], and [[Phoebe Waller-Bridge]].<ref name=casting>{{cite news|url=http://www.mirror.co.uk/tv/tv-news/broadchurch-series-2-eve-myles-3580633|last=Greenwood|first=Carl|title=Broadchurch series 2: Eve Myles, Marianne Jean-Baptiste and James D'Arcy join cast|newspaper=The Daily Mirror|date=21 May 2014|accessdate=24 July 2014}}</ref><ref name=syal>{{cite news|url=http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2014-09-18/meera-syal-to-star-in-broadchurch-series-2|last=Dowell|first=Ben|title=Meera Syal to Star in 'Broadchurch' Series 2|newspaper=Radio Times|date=18 September 2014|accessdate=20 September 2014}}</ref> None of the new characters were connected to the Latimer murder or any other homicide, Chibnall said.<ref name=strangback /> Rampling was named to the cast on 12 May, and Chibnall said her "character is an integral part of the new story".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2014-05-13/charlotte-rampling-to-play-pivotal-role-in-broadchurch-series-2|last=Dowell|first=Ben|title=Charlotte Rampling to play 'pivotal role' in Broadchurch series 2|newspaper=Radio Times|date=13 May 2014|accessdate=3 December 2014}}</ref> He decided to ask Rampling to join the cast after seeing her perform in a [[video art]] piece directed by [[Steve McQueen (director)|Steve McQueen]]. "She was so lively and mischievous but also tough and steely and I thought, that's such a match for how I see this character," Chibnall said.<ref name=cheekiest /> ITV announced that D'Arcy, Jean-Baptiste, Myles, and Waller-Bridge were joining the series on 21 May 2014.<ref name=casting /> Rampling, who lives in France, had seen series one on French television and was a fan of the program. "The sense of community, the idea of solidarity in a small town <U+2014> all that is broken when suspicion starts to creep in. There is something very human about it. You don't know what happens in real life when people suffer this kind of tragedy. People go off and live their lives. But here we can actually accompany them and go through the grieving process with them."<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.express.co.uk/entertainment/tv-radio/549848/Broadchurch-After-cliffhanger-season-two-different-story|last=Rampton|first=James|title=Broadchurch: After the cliffhanger|newspaper=Daily Express|date=3 January 2015|accessdate=4 January 2015}}</ref>

Eve Myles' [[talent agent|agent]] called her on 15 February 2014, just four days after Myles gave birth to her daughter, Sienna, telling Myles of the opportunity to audition for ''Broadchurch''. Myles auditioned on videotape in her home, performing her scenes as swiftly as she could before her child made noise or needed attention. After being cast in series two, Myles received the script for the first episode. "I kept it for bedtime; lights off, ipad out, cup of tea in bed," she said. "It was amazing, like watching a film, the writing is so good. I was shocked, exhilarated and surprised. And it made me laugh."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.david-tennant-news.com/blog/broadchurch-series-2-eve-myles-says-first-script-amazing-like-watching-film/|last=Malkin|first=Diane|title=Broadchurch Series 2: Eve Myles Says The First Script Was 'Amazing, Like Watching a Film'|website=David Tennant News|date=18 December 2014|accessdate=20 December 2014}}</ref> 

Chibnall said he wrote Jean-Baptiste's role specifically for her.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.walesonline.co.uk/whats-on/whats-on-news/eve-myles-join-cast-broadchurch-7149667|last=Owen|first=Cathy|title=Eve Myles to join the cast of Broadchurch for new series|newspaper=Wales Online|date=21 May 2014|accessdate=3 December 2014}}</ref> Baptiste admitted that, living in [[Los Angeles]], [[california]], she was unaware of ''Broadchurch'' and had heard little about the show from friends when she was approached to star in series two. She watched the program and was so impressed that she agreed to star in series two without having seen any of the scripts.<ref name=itvpressrelease>{{cite web|url=http://presscentre.itvstatic.com/presscentre/sites/presscentre/files/Broadchurch%20press%20pack%20S2.pdf|format=PDF|title=Broadchurch Series Two TX January 2015|website=ITV.com|date=18 December 2014|accessdate=4 January 2015}}</ref> Syal's casting was not announced until 18 September 2014<U+2014>about mid-way through filming. Chibnall also described her role as critical to the plot.<ref name=syal />

The role of Nigel Carter's adopted mother was played by Anne Sims, the mother of actor Joe Sims. ''Broadchurch'' series one had photographs of character Nigel Carter with his adopted mother. The production used actual photos of Sims as a child and teenager with his real-life mother, Anne. When series two needed an actress to play Nigel's adopted mother in a few scenes, Sims suggested his own mother play the role. The producers quickly agreed.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.bristolpost.co.uk/Crime-dramas-long-road-gobby-kid-stardom/story-22861702-detail/story.html|title=Bristol actor Joe Sims reveals his long road from 'gobby kid' to stardom|newspaper=The Bristol Post|date=2 September 2014|accessdate=3 December 2014}}</ref>

Eight-month-old twin girls Ava and Millie Priddis also were cast in series two.  The daughters of Luke Priddis and his partner Rosie, of Beacon Heath, [[Exeter]], the girls' paternal grandmother saw a newspaper advertisement for twin babies to appear on television. Although hundreds of twins applied, the producers settled on Ava and Millie just 30 minutes after receiving their photograph. The girls play a role in the Latimer family, but the exact nature of the role was not clear prior to airing.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.exeterexpressandecho.co.uk/Exeter-twins-star-new-series-Broadchurch/story-25807140-detail/story.html|title=Exeter twins to star in new series of Broadchurch|newspaper=Exeter Express and Echo|date=5 January 2015|accessdate=5 January 2015}}</ref>

==Principal photography==
[[James Strong (director)|James Strong]], who directed five of the eight episodes in series one, directed the first two episodes of series two.<ref name=lazaruscasting>{{cite news|url=http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2014-05-12/david-tennant-olivia-colman-and-arthur-darvill-all-return-for-broadchurch-series-two|last=Lazarus|first=Susanna|title=David Tennant, Olivia Colman and Arthur Darvill ALL return for Broadchurch series two|newspaper=Radio Times|date=12 May 2014|accessdate=25 July 2014}}</ref> [[Mike Barker (film director)|Mike Barker]], Jessica Hobbs, and [[Jonathan Teplitzky]] also directed episodes,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mckinneymacartney.com/sound-mixers/Greenhorn-j-drama.html|title=Jim Greenhorn|website=MckinneyMacartney.com|date=30 June 2014|accessdate=6 December 2014}}</ref> with Barker directing episodes seven and eight.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.creativemediamanagement.com/bruce-wills.pdf|format=PDF|title=Bruce Wills - Production Sound Mixer|website=Creative Media Management|date=17 October 2014|accessdate=6 December 2014}}</ref> John Conroy was the [[Cinematographer|director of photography]] for all eight episodes.<ref name=earledream /><ref name=conroy>{{cite web|url=http://www.iftn.ie/news/?act1=record&only=1&aid=73&rid=4287835&tpl=archnews&force=1|last=Brosnan|first=Se<U+00E1>n|title=Interview with John Conroy <U+2013> DOP of upcoming 'Fortitude'|website=The Irish Film & Television Network|date=5 December 2014|accessdate=6 December 2014}}</ref> [[Film editing|Editing]] for series two was overseen by Mike Jones,<ref name=mikejones>{{cite news|url=http://www.dorsetecho.co.uk/news/11251613.Jurassic_classic_location_for_new_series_of_Broadchurch/?ref=var_0|last=Irving|first=Lee|title=Jurassic classic location for new series of Broadchurch|newspaper=Dorset Echo|date=2 June 2014|accessdate=6 December 2014}}</ref> Ben  Lester, Dom Strevens, and Helen Chapman,<ref name=itvpressrelease /> with [[Production designer|production design]] by Simon Rogers<ref name=itvpressrelease /> and [[Art director#In film|art direction]] by John West.<ref name=bectu />

The production was much larger than for the first series. With many scenes taking place outside the small fictional town of Broadchurch, the production expanded away from the Jurassic Coast to include many more locations over a much of Southwest England. With an increase in the size of the cast, this created significant new logistical obstacles. Series two had a concomitant increase in budget, and a much more complex production schedule compared to series one.<ref name=earledream />

===Secrecy===
The plot of series two was a closely guarded secret, and ITV and Kudos held meetings to plan security measures long before shooting began.<ref name=Campellithrill /> Although already one of series two's highest-budget items, the cost of security on series two went significantly over budget as the public and press sought to learn about the plot.<ref name=johnstongood /> All documents were password-protected,<ref name=paynestrict /> and passwords were changed frequently.<ref name=pauleyunprec /> Email and other electronic communications between producers, cast, and crew could only make oblique reference to plot details,<ref name=Campellithrill /> fake emails were circulated to mislead those who might leak them,<ref name=pauleyunprec /> and some emails were coded.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mirror.co.uk/tv/tv-news/broadchurch-season-2-spoilers-creator-4915943|last=Pauley|first=Nigel|title=Broadchurch season 2 spoilers: Creator warns NO ONE is safe as the hit drama returns|newspaper=The Daily Mirror|date=4 January 2015|accessdate=4 January 2015}}</ref> Cast members swore not to reveal any details of series two,<ref name=sneakpreview /><ref name=clue /> and were required to sign legally binding non-disclosure agreements.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailystar.co.uk/showbiz-tv/hot-tv/381513/Broadchurch-Cast-sign-non-disclosure-agreement-Somerset-residents-told-to-keep-quiet|title=Broadchurch: Cast sign non-disclosure plot agreement to hide killer secrets|newspaper=The Daily Star|date=31 May 2014|accessdate=25 July 2014}}</ref><ref name=bathfans /><ref name=gilbertreveal>{{cite news|url=http://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/features/broadchurch-series-2-stars-of-the-awardwinning-show-share-all-the-clues-they-can-9920310.html|last=Gilbert|first=Josh|title=Broadchurch series 2: Olivia Colman, David Tennant and co share all the clues they can|newspaper=The Independent|date=12 December 2014|accessdate=12 December 2014}}</ref> (''[[The Daily Mail]]'' called them "the most rigorous confidentiality agreements in the industry.")<ref name=johnstongood>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/femail/article-2894320/It-s-murderously-good-Intriguing-new-faces-town-torn-apart-grief-mystery-second-series-Broadchurch-better-first.html|last=Johnston|first=Jenny|title=It's murderously good: Intriguing new faces, a town torn apart by grief and another mystery, the second series of Broadchurch will be even better than the first|newspaper=The Daily Mail|date=2 January 2015|accessdate=4 January 2015}}</ref> [[Daily call sheet]]s used pseudonyms for cast members and characters.<ref name=paynestrict>{{cite news|url=http://www.thesun.co.uk/sol/homepage/showbiz/tv/6235803/Is-the-Broadchurch-storyline-best-kept-secret-in-TV-history.html|last=Payne|first=Will|title=Strict silence is ordered in 'Church|newspaper=The Sun|date=5 January 2015|accessdate=5 January 2015}}</ref> Scripts were individually watermarked to prevent them from being photocopied,<ref name=gilbertreveal /><ref name=gilbertnoidea /> used pseudonyms for characters,<ref name=paynestrict /> and were locked away by security guards when not in use by the actors.<ref name=pauleyhacker /><ref name=pauleyunprec>{{cite news|url=http://www.mirror.co.uk/tv/tv-news/broadchurch-plot-secrets-protected-unprecedented-4881689|last=Pauley|first=Nigel|title=Broadchurch plot secrets protected by 'unprecedented security' as drama leads list of 2015's most anticipated shows|newspaper=The Daily Mirror|date=27 December 2014|accessdate=4 January 2015}}</ref> Each actor's or crew member's script had the individual's name watermarked across the page as well, so that leaks could be traced back to the person responsible.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/newsbeat/30680039|last=Holden|first=Steve|title=How producers keep Broadchurch and other TV shows a secret|newspaper=BBC News|date=5 January 2015|accessdate=5 January 2015}}</ref> Actor Andrew Buchan said cast members were told little about the plot, except on a need-to-know basis as they prepared for their performances in each episode.<ref name=independenmidsomer>{{cite news|url=http://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/news/broadchurch-series-2-show-will-be-nothing-like-midsomer-murders-says-star-andrew-buchan-9537491.html|last=Debnath|first=Neela|title=Broadchurch series 2: Show will be 'nothing like Midsomer Murders', says star Andrew Buchan|newspaper=The Independent|date=11 July 2014|accessdate=24 July 2014}}</ref> The actors also received only parts of scripts<ref name=paynestrict /><ref name=pauleyhacker>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/entertainment/tv-radio/even-north-korean-hackers-couldnt-4881950|last=Pauley|first=Nigel|title=Even North Korean hackers couldn't crack script of second series of hit TV thriller Broadchurch|newspaper=The Daily Record|date=28 December 2014|accessdate=4 January 2015}}</ref> and only two scripts at a time to ensure that they did not know story details too far in advance.<ref name=simsreturns /><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cheddarvalleygazette.co.uk/Broadchurch-series-2-filming-photos-West-Bay/story-22931887-detail/story.html|last=Mat|first=Ian|title=Broadchurch series 2 filming photos in West Bay, Dorset|newspaper=Cheddar Valley Gazette|date=16 September 2014|accessdate=6 December 2014}}</ref> Cinematographer John Conroy said the cast and crew did not know how series two ended until three weeks before shooting began on the final two scripts,<ref name=conroy /> Two former [[Coldstream Guards]] were hired to stand in front of news reporters when they visited the set, to block possible photographs of the filming.<ref name=gilbertreveal /> Several different endings for series two were filmed,<ref name=cheekiest /><ref name=pauleyhacker /> the cast was not permitted to see completed episodes of the series,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/british-tv/s218/broadchurch/news/a619248/arthur-darvill-on-broadchurch-actors-arent-allowed-to-see-any-of-it.html|last=Alexander|first=Susannah|title=Arthur Darvill on Broadchurch: 'Actors aren't allowed to see any of it'|website=Digital Spy UK|date=5 January 2015|accessdate=5 January 2015}}</ref> and Chibnall said that cast members will remain in the dark about the program's outcome until the final episode airs.<ref name=cheekiest />

ITV held no preview screenings of series two with the press.<ref name=gilbertnoidea>{{cite news|url=http://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/life/features/weve-no-clue-who-will-turn-out-to-be-the-killer-30871979.html|last=Gilbert|first=Gerard|title='We've no clue who will turn out to be the killer'|newspaper=Belfast Telegraph|date=3 January 2015|accessdate=4 January 2015}}</ref> News media, however, revealed some aspects of the plot as filming occurred. Producer Richard Stokes revealed in October 2013 that most of the action in the second series would not take place in the fictional town of Broadchurch, but another fictional town. The Broadchurch name was retained, however, because "[it's] a brand and it's gained huge popularity so you can't risk losing that by changing the name."<ref name=mysterydeepens /> Press outlets confirmed in March 2014 that at least part of the second series would still take place in the fictional town of Broadchurch.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.bridportnews.co.uk/news/11104052.West_Bay_set_to_be_a_Broadchurch_star_again/|last=Bell|first=Anne|title=West Bay set to be a Broadchurch star again|newspaper=Bridport News|date=26 March 2014|accessdate=3 November 2014}}</ref><ref name=lazaruscasting /> At least one scene was filmed in a cemetery, and others depicted a very pregnant Beth Latimer.<ref name=independenmidsomer />

The secrecy campaign was critised by reporter Susanna Lazarus of ''Radio Times''. While generally decrying the over-use of plot highlights and one-liners in film and television marketing, she argued that there was nonetheless a role for [[Spoiler (media)|spoilers]] so that audiences could decide which shows to watch among the wide array of media choices. There was a "thin line", she said, between too much and too little information, but she asked the producers of ''Broadchurch'' to walk it.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2015-01-05/broadchurch-is-no-spoilers-a-good-thing|last=Lazarus|first=Susanna|title=Broadchurch: is no spoilers a good thing?|newspaper=Radio Times|date=5 January 2015|accessdate=5 January 2015}}</ref>

===Location shooting===
[[File:Beach, West Bay - geograph.org.uk - 1288472.jpg|thumb|Harbour Cliff and Harbour Cliff Beach, the most prominent locations used in ''Broadchurch''.]]
[[File:St Andrews church - geograph.org.uk - 288601.jpg|thumb|St Andrew's Church, Clevedon, provided exteriors and interiors for the fictional Broadchurch parish church.]]
[[File:Weymouth Harbour 2005 from the south side showing The George Inn.jpg|thumb|Weymouth Harbour, used for exterior shots in series two.]]
[[File:Reading Prison 1.JPG|thumb|HM Prison Reading provided interior and exterior locations for the fictional Wessex Prison.]]
[[File:Exeter reception.JPG|thumb|The Forum building at the University of Exeter (''shown here at night'') served as both the fictiional Wessex Police headquarters and the Wessex Crown Court.]]
Much of ''Broadchurch'' series two was shot on location. Chibnall felt location shooting was critical to the mood and tone of series two, much as it was for series one. While many crime dramas are shot in gritty, urban locations, Chibnall believed that the bucolic Jurassic Coast setting signaled to viewers that ''Broadchurch'' was not a typical detective program.<ref name=mikejones /> Producer Richard Stokes said that the Dorset area provided "that sense of the extraordinary, [that] the tragic and the terrible [can] happen in a rather beautiful and moving environment."<ref name=mikejones /> Early in the pre-production process, the producers and location managers discussed filming in locations other than Dorset. Among the areas considered were cliff locations near [[Bristol]]; [[Essex]]; [[Hastings]] in [[East Sussex]]; [[Kent]]; and [[Weston-super-Mare]] in [[Somerset]]. But the producers felt none of the locations could replicate the look of the Jurassic Coast, and the quality of the light in each area was different than in Dorset.<ref name=mikejones />

Filming began in late May 2014, with the first cast [[read-through]] occurring on 22 May.<ref name=dorsetechofirst>{{cite news|url=http://www.dorsetecho.co.uk/news/11230713.First_read_through_for_Broadchurch_2_takes_place/|title=First read-through for Broadchurch 2 takes place|newspaper=The Dorset Echo|date=22 May 2014|accessdate=25 July 2014}}</ref> About 70 cast and crew worked on ''Broadchurch'' series two, and each episode took 12 and a half days to complete.<ref name=simsreturns /> Joel Holmes was the production's location manager.<ref>{{cite report|url=http://Fwww.clevedon.gov.uk/controls/DownloadDocument.ashx?docID=zi5473JQMOCCWHYPWN3617oGxj%26aID=4710|author=Clevedon Town Council|title=Minutes of the Town Events & Amenities Committee|date=1 October 2014|page=722|format=PDF}}</ref> The code name "Tea and Sympathy" was used as a cover to disguise as much of the production's activities as possible.<ref name=filmingends />

Shooting primarily occurred in the counties of [[Berkshire]],<ref name=readingspotted /> [[Devon]], [[Dorset]], and [[Somerset]].<ref name=independenmidsomer /> Most filming occurred in the town of [[Clevedon]] in Somerset.<ref name=tenanttoexeter /><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.exeterexpressandecho.co.uk/David-Tennant-rumoured-Exeter-University-filming/story-21231954-detail/story.html|title=David Tennant rumoured to be at Exeter University filming new series of Broadchurch|newspaper=Exeter Express and Echo|date=13 June 2014|accessdate=6 December 2014}}</ref> The production spent nearly three months filming at the [[University of Exeter]] in the city of [[Exeter]] in Devon.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.exeterexpressandecho.co.uk/Broadchurch-filming-continue-Exeter-summer-David/story-21232686-detail/story.html|last=Walmesley|first=Adam|title=Broadchurch filming to continue in Exeter through summer as David Tennant spotted during recording on university campus|newspaper=Exeter Express and Echo|date=13 June 2014|accessdate=6 December 2014}}</ref> Extensive shooting was also done in [[West Bay, Dorset|West Bay]] in Dorset, where the production used the Station Road Car Park for its production trailers and offices.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.bridportnews.co.uk/news/11510293.Public_outrage_at_lack_of_consultation_for_council_car_park/?ref=mr|last=Gerryts|first=Rene|title=Public outrage at lack of consultation for council car park|newspaper=Bridport News|date=2 October 2014|accessdate=6 December 2014}}</ref> A car park next to the West Bay Hotel in [[Bridport]] served as the production's base camp while filming in that area,<ref name=bridport /><ref name=irvingroll>{{cite news|url=http://www.dorsetecho.co.uk/news/broadchurch/11258257.Cameras_roll_as_stars_return_for_filming_of_Broadchurch_2/|last=Irving|first=Lee|title=Cameras roll as stars return for filming of Broadchurch 2|newspaper=Dorset Echo|date=5 June 2014|accessdate=5 December 2014}}</ref> while the Rivermead Leisure Centre car park served as production headquarters in [[Reading, Berkshire|Reading]], Berkshire.<ref name=readingspotted /> The John Nike Leisuresport Complex served as production headquarters in [[Bracknell]], Berkshire.<ref name=bracknell />

On 20 December 2014, Chibnall revealed that a blue [[Clapboard (architecture)|clapboard]] chalet is integral to the mystery presented in series two. Chibnall said the chalet is where "lots <U+2014> if not all <U+2014> of the secrets" of series two are hidden, and that the chalet (just {{convert|200|yd|m}} from the site of Danny's murder in series one, according to the show's geography) will be seen in the first minute of episode one.<ref name=cheekiest />
