| <ref name=daviesbehind>{{cite news|url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/broadchurch/11318738/Broadchurch-Series-2-behind-the-scenes.html|last=Davis|first=Sereena|title=Broadchurch Series 2: behind the scenes|newspaper=The Daily Telegraph|date=3 January 2015|date=4 January 2015|postscript=none}}; {{cite news|url=http://www.mirror.co.uk/tv/tv-news/broadchurch-behind-scenes-show-creator-4921867|last=Shenton|first=Zoe|title=Broadchurch behind the scenes: Show creator Chris Chibnall reveals secrets from new series|newspaper=The Daily Mirror|date=5 January 2015|date=5 January 2015}}</ref>
|}
<br><br>
David Tennant took a break from filming the second series to shoot episodes of ''Broadchurch''{{'s}} American remake, ''Gracepoint''. He returned to the ''Broadchurch'' series two production about 15 September 2014.<ref name=tennantreturns />

The production team was strongly criticised by the West Bay Coastguards in June 2014 for filming too close to the edge of East Cliff at West Bay. Severe weather and recent rockslides left the cliffs unstable, and a Coastguard volunteer said the production team should have used stakes, safety lines, harnesses, and helmets. A spokesperson for the ''Broadchurch'' production defended the film crew, noting that the production team received all necessary filming permits, visited the site numerous times to ensure safety, and took other reasonable health and safety precautions.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/10884915/PLS-PIC-and-PUB-Broadchurch-crew-criticised-for-unnecessary-silly-risk-by-filming-at-dangerous-cliff-edge.html|last=Furness|first=Hannah|title=Broadchurch crew criticised for 'unnecessary, silly risk' by filming at dangerous cliff edge|newspaper=The Daily Telegraph|date=8 June 2014|accessdate=9 November 2014}}</ref>

Filming for series two of ''Broadchurch 2'' concluded just before midnight on 12 October 2014.<ref name=filmingends /><ref name=echofilmingends>{{cite news|url=http://www.bournemouthecho.co.uk/news/11538327.EXCLUSIVE__Broadchurch_2_producer_thanks_West_Dorset_residents_for_their_support_during_filming/|last=Gerryts|first=Rene|title=EXCLUSIVE: Broadchurch 2 producer thanks West Dorset residents for their support during filming|newspaper=Bournemouth Echo|date=16 October 2014|accessdate=25 October 2014}}</ref> Final scenes were shot at the village of Eype.<ref name=filmingends />

===Studio shooting and shooting schedule===
Unlike the first series, series two contained a great deal of studio filming. Chibnall said this was because of the changed nature of the story, and he said that nearly all the major story moments in the second series occurred on a stage.<ref name=gilbertreveal /> David Tennant said that while the Jurassic Coast and several locations from series one are still featured in series two, most shooting occurred on studio sets near London.<ref name=coastline>{{cite news|url=http://www.dorsetecho.co.uk/news/11673792.Coastline_inspires_stars_of_hit_TV_drama/|last=Davis|first=Joanna|title=Coastline inspires stars of hit TV drama Broadchurch|newspaper=Dorset Echo|date=18 December 2014|accessdate=18 December 2014}}</ref>

Some sets were built at [[Longcross Studios]] in [[Longcross]], [[Surrey]], where art director John West built a very large set.<ref name=bectu>{{cite web|url=https://www.bectu.org.uk/advice-resources/crewbus/234058f7d692a0bfc8b3e2c2190d6cb0?image=305|title=John West|website=BECTU.org.uk|date=2014|accessdate=6 December 2014}}</ref>{{Efn|The decision to film near [[London]] was apparently made before series one ended. According to Olivia Colman, the decision to shoot on soundstages near London was done to benefit those cast members whose families lived in the city.}}<ref name=halinawatts /> Additional scenes were shot at North Light Film Studios in [[Armitage Bridge]], [[West Yorkshire]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.examiner.co.uk/news/west-yorkshire-news/north-light-film-studios-armitage-7658559|last=Himelfield|first=Dave|title=Armitage Bridge's North Light Film Studios chosen for film 'The Incident' starring Ruta Gedmintas|newspaper=Huddersfield Examiner|date=22 August 2014|accessdate=6 December 2014|postscript=none}}; {{cite news|url=http://www.examiner.co.uk/news/west-yorkshire-news/armitage-bridge-environmentally-friendly-hair-7678757|last=Himelfield|first=Dave|title=Armitage Bridge environmentally friendly hair salon Eclips Hair and Beauty Rooms is a cut above|newspaper=Huddersfield Examiner|date=28 August 2014|accessdate=6 December 2014}}</ref> Olivia Colman

===Acting===
The casting of Rampling led to apprehension among many series two cast members, who were intimidated by her. But Chris Chibnall said that Rampling's humor (she's "a proper giggler") alleviated this immediately.<ref name=ramplingexotic /> Colman described Marianne Jean-Baptiste as "the coolest women on the planet", and said that Eve Myles and Phoebe Waller-Bridge (a long-time friend of Colman's) both had a terrific sense of humor to the production.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.walesonline.co.uk/whats-on/film-news/broadchurch-8375317|last=McCrum|first=Kirstie|title='Like going back to a childhood holiday' - we quiz Olivia Colman on the return of ITV's Broadchurch|website=Wales Online|date=3 January 2015|accessdate=4 January 2015}}</ref>

Chibnall had particular praise for Olivia Colman's performance. "She's got such range, Olivia. ... She can do anything I throw at her <U+2014> she's a writer's dream."<ref name=earledream />

==Musical soundtrack==
Icelandic musician and composer <U+00D3>lafur Arnalds{{Efn|This is an Icelandic name. The last name is a family name, but in Iceland people are properly referred to by their given name, e.g., <U+00D3>lafur.}} composed the music for ''Broadchurch'' series two, as he did for series one.<ref name=itvpressrelease /> <U+00D3>lafur met with Chibnall and the other producers to discuss the score on 16 August 2014,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/OlafurArnalds/status/500590741148950528|title=The first Broadchurch 2 score meeting took place this morning in London. Exciting times ahead!|website=@OlafurArnalds at Twitter.com|date=16 August 2014|accessdate=4 December 2014}}</ref> and began work on the soundtrack the first week of September.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://drownedinsound.com/in_depth/4148147-dis-meets-lafur-arnalds-there-is-no-real-music-business-there-you-can-t-get-famous|last=Martin|first=Erin Lyndal|title=DiS meets <U+00D3>lafur Arnalds - 'There is no real music business there... You can't get famous'|website=Drowned in Sound|date=11 September 2014|accessdate=4 January 2015}}</ref>

<U+00D3>lafur [[Twitter]]ed on 8 October that the series two soundtrack would have a much stronger [[percussion]] sound. Doddi, a member of the musical quartet that performs with <U+00D3>lafur in live shows, provided the percussion music and sounds for the new soundtrack.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/OlafurArnalds/status/519948022042877952|title=I felt #Broadchurch needed more rhythm this year|website=@OlafurArnalds at Twitter.com|date=8 October 2014|accessdate=4 December 2014|postscript=none}}; {{cite web|url=http://moreintelligentlife.com/blog/paul-sullivan/qa-%C3%B3lafur-arnalds-musician|last=Sullivan|first=Paul|title=The Q&A: <U+00D3>lafur Arnalds, Musician, Experimentalist|website=More Intelligent Life|date=2013|accessdate=4 December 2014}}</ref> <U+00D3>lafur reported on 26 August that the opening episode involved a 10 minute long sequence underscored with music.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/OlafurArnalds/status/504292777057071105|title=Feeling a bit overwhelmed by the fact that Episode 1 of Broadchurch 2 starts with a big 10 minute music cue! Better get to work...|website=@OlafurArnalds at Twitter.com|date=26 August 2014|accessdate=4 December 2014}}</ref> The composer finished writing the first musical cue for episode one on 10 October,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/OlafurArnalds/status/520717655310094336|title=Broadchurch2 - Episode1 - Cue1. Done! http://|website=@OlafurArnalds at Twitter.com|date=10 October 2014|accessdate=4 December 2014}}</ref> and began recording the [[string section|strings]] music for series two on 11 November.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/OlafurArnalds/status/532160852397273089|title=Broadchurch season 2 string recordings today!|website=@OlafurArnalds at Twitter.com|date=11 November 2014|accessdate=4 December 2014}}</ref> Music for the second episode of series two was delivered on 14 November 2014.<ref name=eptwomusicdone>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/OlafurArnalds/status/533093832301506560|title=Delivering the first episode of Broadchurch S2 tomorrow|website=@OlafurArnalds at Twitter.com|date=13 November 2014|accessdate=4 December 2014}}</ref>

<U+00D3>lafur Twittered on 13 November 2014 that he and longtime collaborator, singer Arn<U+00F3>r Dan of the Icelandic band [[Agent Fresco]], had written a new closing theme for each episode of series two.<ref name=eptwomusicdone /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/Arnor_Dan/status/534330073374261248|title=Did me and @OlafurArnalds just write and record a new end theme for the second season of @BroadchurchTV? YOU BETCHA!!|website=@Arnor_Dan at Twitter.com|date=17 November 2014|accessdate=4 December 2014}}</ref>

Susanna Lazarus at ''Radio Times'' described the soundtrack as full of "ethereal vocals and haunting music".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2014-12-11/broadchurch-series-two-trailer-what-have-we-learned|last=Lazarus|first=Susanna|title=Broadchurch series two trailer: what have we learned?|newspaper=Radio Times|date=11 December 2014|accessdate=11 December 2014}}</ref>

==Post-production==
The [[post-production]] process was a lengthy one. Actress Jodie Whittaker said that the cast would not able to preview their performances before they aired on ITV in January.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2014-12-05/broadchurchs-jodie-whittaker-we-were-emotional-wrecks-on-set-but-david-tennant-held-it-together|last=Lazarus|first=Susanna|title=Broadchurch's Jodie Whittaker: we were emotional wrecks on set but David Tennant held it together|newspaper=Radio Times|date=5 December 2014|accessdate=9 December 2014}}</ref>

Audio post-production was overseen by Sonorous, a company founded in 2013 by Howard Bargroff. Sound mixing was done using [[PMC Ltd.]]{{'s}} twotwo.6s nearfield [[studio monitor]]s.<ref name=iabm>{{cite web|url=http://www.theiabm.org/news/latest-news/latest-news_detail.sherlock-broadchurch-mix-engineer-installs-pmc-in-dubbing-room.html|title=Sherlock & Broadchurch Mix Engineer Installs PMC In Dubbing Room|website=International Association of Broadcasting Manufacturers|date=12 November 2014|accessdate=9 December 2014}}</ref>{{efn|"Nearfield" loudspeakers are those which are intended to be three times closer to the listener than the nearest hard surface. Nearfield listening reduces echo, and reduces the impact which poor room [[acoustics]] may have on sound.}}{{sfn|Rose|2014|page=34}}

==Marketing==
On 9 November 2014, two 20-second teaser trailers began airing on ITV, each titled "The End Is Where It Begins".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2014-11-09/the-end-is-where-it-begins-in-the-first-teasers-for-broadchurch-series-two|last=Lazarus|first=Susanna|title='The End Is Where It Begins' in the first teasers for Broadchurch series two|newspaper=[[Radio Times]]|date=9 November 2014|accessdate=9 November 2014}}</ref> On 16 November 2014, a third 20-second teaser trailer aired on ITV, in two versions, voiced by characters Alec Hardy and Ellie Miller, respectively. These were also titled "The End Is Where It Begins".<ref name=goodacreconfirmed>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/british-tv/s218/broadchurch/news/a610483/broadchurch-series-2-january-2015-return-date-confirmed-in-new-teasers.html|last=Goodacre|first=Kate|title='Broadchurch series 2: January 2015 return date confirmed in new teasers|website=[[Digital Spy]]|date=16 November 2014|accessdate=16 November 2014|}}</ref>

A fourth series two trailer was released on 11 December, with ITV announcing a series two air date of 5 January 2015.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mirror.co.uk/tv/tv-news/watch-new-broadchurch-series-2-4792062|last=Walker|first=Danny|title=Watch new Broadchurch series 2 trailer as David Tennant promises he 'can't do it on his own'|newspaper=The Daily Mirror|date=11 December 2014|accessdate=11 December 2014}}</ref> ITV released only a small portion of the full trailer at first, and said it would release longer versions on YouTube as the [[hashtag]] #BroadchurchReturns was [[Twitter|tweeted]] a certain number of times. (The network did not disclose the retweet goals it established.) ITV executive creative director Tony Pipes said the goal was to generate online buzz about series two.<ref name=campellikickoff />

Other marketing efforts included an [[Below the line (advertising)|above the line]]" online advertising campaign. This consisted primarily of a linear advertising campaign.{{Efn|Linear advertising is marketing which is straightforward and occurs during a specific time for a predetermined duration. This kind of advertising treats all consumers as the same, and does not seek to target subsegments of the population. Linear advertising does not change if it recurs.}}{{sfn|Hackley|2005|pages=30-31}} ITV also said it would begin [[billboard]] advertising after Christmas 2014.<ref name=campellikickoff />

Another marketing component involved the publication of short stories after each episode airs. Chibnall was so enthused by author Erin Kelly's novelisation of ''Broadchurch'' series one that ITV contracted with her to write a short story to accompany each episode. The short stories, each to be published individually as an [[e-book]], focus on a single character from series two.<ref name=lazaruscertain />

